[2]
Date: 25 Dec 2006
From: Pablo Nart <Pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: Horsetalk [edited]
<http://www.horsetalk.co.nz/news/0612/086.shtml>

5th horse dies in equine herpes outbreak
---------------------------------------------
A 5th horse in Florida died on Friday [22 Dec 2006] of equine herpes
(or EHV-1, equine rhinopneumontis) at Payson Park, a 500-horse
facility in Martin County, which is now under state quarantine; 9
other equine facilities are also under quarantine.
The Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services believes
the horse was infected at Wellington's Palm Beach Equine Sports
Complex, the common link in all 10 of the known cases.
The department is looking at ways to properly dispose of manure
[contaminated with the virus], which can live in bedding and manure
for up to 28 days. It may be burned on site or removed to another
site for disposal.
The equestrian community in Ocala is concerned about the outbreak,
and state equine veterinarian Dr. Michael Short told a meeting late
last week that there were "a lot of rumors out there ... and most of
them are false."
The community is worried that panic over the virus in the region
could hurt the industry, which is worth more than USD 2 billion a
year in Florida.
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo.nart@terra.es>
